But some low income women continued to practice unsafe abortions by inserting rods into their womb, or by taking a brew of chemicals concocted from water, garlic and ting zi rao (a traditional East Asian immuno-stimulant plant).

These women sometimes required hospitalization following dangerous attempts to perform unsafe abortions. An awful example of this dangerous practice took place in Inner Mongolia after a regional priest was accompanied by a number of women to a local hospital to treat what appeared to be nosebleeds.

The priest and the women had previously washed the nose of the women with salt water and alcohol. The women was then made to take herbs that were believed to address their medical condition.

While hospital officials did treat the woman, her symptoms suggested that she didn’t have a nose injury; instead, she was a victim of an unsafe abortion. She was also receiving consistent treatment for lung infections.

One side of the pregnancy debate alleges weak enforcement of the new abortion law weakening it; the other side claims that relatively few abortions are taking place. Both sides are probably correct, and strong laws are unlikely to solve the problem as had been dexterously formulated in safe abortion legislation in recent years.
